For Dialogue, we're just creating a class under the Server/src/main/java/com/rs/game/player/dialogues/cities/ and
either creating a city directory or we are using an existing.

To be less sloppy unless you have multiple npcs such as a quest, we're going to define the npcID.

private int npcId == whatever the npc id is.

private means that the variable is only being used in this class, int is short for integer since we the id is
a whole number.

Facial Expressions that are defined: NORMAL,QUESTIONS,MAD,MOCK,LAUGHING,WORRIED, HAPPY, CONFUSED,DRUNK, ANGRY, SAD, SCARED.

To send a player chat: sendPlayerDialogue(FacialExpression, "A random string");
To send a Npc Chat: sendNPCDialogue(npcId, FacialExpression, "String");
To send am Option chat: sendOptionDialouge(title, "options", "options";

For Option Dialogue, you can use only one option if you'd like but that's lame when you could use a player dialogue as a reponse without
the options.

The title is what you see at the top of the options interface.

You start under "start" and you either send player dialogue, options, or npc dialogue.
Once you've added this, you declare the stage of dialogue you are on. We always start with -1

It should look like this: stage = -1;

Under the run function -> run()

We start to add more. For example, We declare the stage now.
if ( stage == -1 ) { sendNPCDialogue(npcId, HAPPY, "Wow, learning how to write Dialogue is so much fun!" );

So if is a statement ( if this happens then do this ), We are saying if the stage is equal to -1, we continue with this. We sent the npc dialogue
and now we close with setting the stage.

if ( stage == -1 ) { sendNPCDialogue(npcId, HAPPY, "Wow, learning how to write Dialogue is so much fun!" );
stage = 0;
}
